Exercise 14.1: In what ways does an overloaded operator differ from a
built-in operator? In what ways are overloaded operators the same as the
built-in operators?

Answer:
They are the same for:
*  They both have the same precedence and associativity.
They are different for:
* An overloaded function can be called directly.
* An overloaded function must be a member of a class or at least have one class type.
* Only some of overloaded operator retain the same guarantee the order in which operands are evaluated.

